{{about|the restaurant in Los Angeles|the Canadian television series|The Pig and Whistle}} {{Infobox restaurant | name = Pig 'n Whistle | logo = | logo_width = | logo_alt = | image = File:2014.04.10.pig.and.whistle.6712.hollywood.blvd.jpg | image_width = 160px | image_alt = | image_caption = | pushpin_map = | map_width = | map_alt = | map_caption = | slogan = | established = {{Start date|1927|07|22}} | closed = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | current-owner = | previous-owner = | chef = | head-chef = | food-type = American | dress-code = [[Casual attire|Casual]], [[business casual]] | rating = | street-address = 6714 [[Hollywood Boulevard]] | city = [[Hollywood, Los Angeles|Hollywood]], [[Los Angeles]] | county = [[Los Angeles]] | state = [[California]] | postcode = | country = [[United States]] | coordinates = {{Coord|34.1014|-118.33673|type:landmark_region:US-CA|display=inline,title}} | seating-capacity = | reservations = | other-locations = | other-information = | website = {{URL|http://www.pignwhistlehollywood.com}} }}
The '''''Pig 'n Whistle''''' is an American restaurant and bar<ref name=pillow>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/may/20/news/cl-152 |work=The Los Angeles Times|title=Pillow Talk at the Pig|date=May 20, 2001|author=Maria Elena Fernandez}}</ref> located in [[Hollywood, Los Angeles|Hollywood]]<ref name=twist>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2012/may/17/entertainment/la-et-cm-it-is-done-pig-n-whistle-20120516|work=The Los Angeles Times|title=Review: A twist to 'It Is Done' at the Pig 'N Whistle|date=May 17, 2012|author=Margaret Gray}}</ref> on [[Hollywood Boulevard]].<ref name=open>{{cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/westcoastsound/2014/02/20/ten-great-la-music-open-mic-nights |work=LA Weekly|title=Ten Great L.A. Open Mic Nights for Music|author=Paul T. Bradley|date=February 20, 2014}}</ref>
==History== [[File:1908.12.17.LAT.advert.for.downtown.location.of.pig.and.whistle.png|thumb|200px|left|1908 [[Los Angeles Times]] Advertisement for original Pig 'n Whistle in Downtown Los Angeles]] The Pig 'n Whistle was originally a chain of restaurants and candy shops, founded by John Gage in 1908.<ref name=gelakoska/>{{rp|7}} He opened his first location in [[Downtown Los Angeles]], next to the now-demolished third city hall in the 200 block of South [[Broadway (Los Angeles)|Broadway]].<ref name=gelakoska/>{{rp|7}}
The Hollywood location of the ''Pig 'n Whistle'' was first opened in 1927<ref name=gelakoska>{{cite book|author=Veronica Gelakoska|title=Pig 'n Whistle|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ioobrcaDfdAC&pg=PA58|date=October 2010|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-8141-5|page=58}}</ref> next to ''[[Grauman's Egyptian Theatre|The Egyptian Theatre]]''.<ref name=rise>{{cite news|work=The Los Angeles Times|title=Buildings Rise in Hollywood|date=July 17, 1927|page=E1}}</ref> The building housing the new restaurant cost $225,000 and featured "[c]arved oak rafters, imported tiles, artistically wrought grilles and balcony and great panelled fresco paintings from Don Quixote."<ref name=rise/> It was frequented by such celebrities as [[Spencer Tracy]], [[Shirley Temple]] and [[Howard Hughes]].<ref name=silk>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2001/apr/26/news/cl-55632 |work=The Los Angeles Times|title=A Silk Purse Out of a Sow's Ear|date=April 26, 2001|author=Scarlet Cheng}}</ref> The original Hollywood location closed down after [[World War II]]<ref name=returns>{{cite news|title=The Best...the Beautiful...and the Bizarre; PORKY'S II; The Pig"n Whistle Returns|date=October 24, 1999|author=Ed Liebowitz|work=The Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1999/oct/24/magazine/tm-27721}}</ref> and its distinctive wooden furniture, decorated with hand-carved whistle-playing pigs,<ref name=returns/> was sold to [[Miceli's Italian Restaurant]], located around the corner at 1646 Las Palmas Avenue, where it remains to the present day.<ref name=danced>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-07-15/news/we-470_1_hollywood-blvd|title=Where Pigs Danced and Waitresses Reached for Stars|work=The Los Angeles Times|page=WSJ8|date=July 15, 1990|author=Michael Szymanski}}</ref>
By the late 1990s the location housed a fast-food pizza restaurant, and all that remained of the original tenant was a bas-relief pig on the front of the building.<ref name=danced/> In 1999, British restaurant operator Chris Breed remodeled the building, recovering the spectacular original ceiling ornamentation, and re-opened the restaurant.<ref name=returns/>
The restaurant name originates from two [[Old English]] words, piggin, a lead mug, and wassail, a wine drunk during yuletide.<ref name=silk/>
